el hand-lettered, and inside, in a neat avalanche of tabs and invoices and contracts, was the vendor list and a receipt stamped with a number that made me do the quick mental math that keeps me from spiraling: primo deposito €4,500, catering deposit owed by next Tuesday, transport guests from Positano €600 plus tip. My shoulders dropped a fraction. Numbers didn't plead.\n\nI flipped through tabs with practiced efficiency, fingers making tiny legal motions. \"Chair supplier?\"\n\n\"Napoli,\" Enzo said, tapping a diagram with a scarred finger. \"Wood, folding. Not cheap.\"\n\n\"Contact info? Deposit status?\"\n\nDante leaned closer, his breath warm with espresso. \"Breathe, counselor. Everything's handled.\"\n\nHis hands were broad and smelled of basil when he gestured toward the catering tab.\n\nI stared up from the binder. \"Define 'handled.'\"\n\n\"Paid, confirmed, triple-checked.\" He touched the corner of the page, leaving a small grease smudge. \"What else you need?\"\n\nEnzo cleared his throat, sliding a photocopied invoice across the stone. \"Gianna left the seating chart. Exact placement for the chapel.\"\n\nSofia's signature sat at the bottom with a handwritten note in careful script: 'Favor le grapes for Sunday—Dante.'\n\nI scribbled notes in my notebook—neat as a summons—then looked up at the terrace that folded away into lemon trees and the sea beyond the cliff, at the nave of the monastery repurposed with white chairs and lanterns.\n\nThe monastery smelled of old limewash and frying garlic somewhere distant; a sun-bleached plastic water bottle had lodged in the drainpipe near the third step, half-covered in sand, the supermarket label flaking off with a barcode that didn't belong in a place posted on travel brochures. That little wrongness kept me honest. But then I reached out to touch the warm stone wall, feeling the ancient texture under my palm, the way centuries of weather had smoothed the edges.\n\nI snapped the binder shut. \"Nobody shows up without signed contracts.\"\n\nDante crossed his arms, flour rubbing into his cuff. \"You always this trusting?\"\n\n\"I'm a divorce attorney. Trust is a luxury I can't afford.\"\n\nHe studied my face for a long moment. \"Must get lonely.\"\n\nThe words hit closer than I expected. I tucked the linen sample back into my bag, burying the memory of Marco's shirts under the fabric like evidence sealed away.\n\nDante stepped closer, close enough that I could see the gold flecks in his dark eyes, close enough that his voice dropped to something meant only for me.\n\n\"You know what I think?\" he said, his thumb brushing flour from the edge of the binder still clutched in my hands. \"I think you came here for more than just Sofia's wedding.\"\n\nMy breath caught. The way he said it—not a question, but a recognition of something I hadn't even admitted to myself.\n\n\"I think,\" he continued, his voice soft as the morning breeze carrying lemon blossoms, \"you're running from something.",
