n. \"Marco handles all the family stuff.\" He glanced at his aunt. \"Keeps everyone from—\"\n\n\"From killing each other,\" Marco finished. His shoulders went tight. He smoothed one of his sketches flat against the bench, and the purple ink bled into the stone where the paper's edge hung over. \"Mamma gets... she needs someone who can navigate the minefield.\"\n\n\"Without detonating anything important,\" Dante added quietly.\n\nGianna's chin lifted. \"I am perfectly reasonable.\"\n\n\"Of course you are.\" Dante's voice was too quick, too bright.\n\nI pressed my thumb to the sketch to keep it from sliding toward the fountain, and something crinkled underneath. Another piece of paper, smaller, folded tight. The purple smudge came off on my skin as I worked it free. Same handwriting, but this was a list. Names in neat columns, and next to one of them—mine—someone had written EXCLUDE in block letters that devoured half the margin.\n\nI peeled the paper free and held it out to Marco. \"Explain this.\"\n\nMarco took the paper like it might bite him. His eyes tracked across the writing, and I watched his jaw work as he read. The fountain gurgled behind us, the only sound cutting through the sudden silence. A bead of sweat rolled down his temple despite the shade from the monastery's ancient walls.\n\n\"This isn't...\" He stared up at me, then at Sofia, then back at the paper. \"This is from weeks ago. Before we knew you were coming.\"\n\n\"Before you knew I existed, you mean.\" I crossed my arms, the stone bench warm against my thighs where I leaned back. \"So someone just preemptively decided I was unwelcome?\"\n\nGianna cleared her throat, a delicate sound that somehow commanded attention. \"The guest list has been... evolving.\" She adjusted her silk scarf. \"There are considerations—\"\n\n\"What considerations?\" The courtroom voice came back, sharp enough to cut. Even the cicadas paused. \"I'm Sofia's maid of honor. I'm already here. What exactly am I being excluded 