 cliffs below. \"Midnight is cutting it close.\"\n\nWe worked like opposing counsel on the same side. I built the legal framework, he negotiated the ground solution. Twenty minutes later I sent an email that launched with \"Sustained\" and ended with a non-negotiable deadline. Marco pocketed his phone after promising Salerno double overtime, his shoulders finally relaxing for the first time since the crisis began.\n\nThe assistant laughed when Marco delivered another curse in that flat tone that cuts through chaos better than shouting. I slid the highlighted contract clause across the table, the paper making a soft whisper against the stone surface.\n\nMarco picked it up, scanning the text. \"This covers us?\"\n\n\"Better than covers us. It buries—\"\n\nHe met my eyes, then flicked the buttercream off his thumb with a quick nod. The gesture was so matter-of-fact, so practical, that it made me want to smile despite everything.\n\nThe monastery clock chimed twice. We both stood, the movement synchronized without discussion.\n\nMarco checked his screen and his face changed. \"Merda.\" He peered up. \"Photographer wants to move ceremony shots to tomorrow morning. Weather forecast shows rain during reception.\"\n\nAnother variable. I grabbed my phone, thumb already moving across the screen. \"That means re-coordinating with the florist. And checking Sofia's schedule.\"\n\nHe was already dialing.\n\nHours later, after endless calls and negotiations, dawn broke over the monastery walls. Marco checked his screen and his face changed. \"Merda.\" He looked up. \"Photographer wants to move ceremony shots to tomorrow morning. Weather forecast shows rain during reception.\"",
