h when I said it was genuine this time, not the careful sound he'd been making all day.\n\n\"I'd like to redirect.\" I tucked a strand from my face. \"You're assuming the answer.\"\n\nHe spun back to me, eyebrow raised in that way that used to make my pulse skip. \"Counselor, you walked out here on your own.\"\n\nThere we were, doing our old dance—evidence, counters, the ritualized tucking away of anything that might unravel the rest of the week. The fairy light stuttered and steadied. A breeze lifted off the water, carrying the smell of brine and something else, something green and wild from the cliffs.\n\nHe watched me like someone mapping a tricky negotiation. \"I kept Luca together after Dad died.\" He ran his free thumb along his jaw. \"Fifteen years old, trying to be his father.\"\n\nThe sentence landed like a coin on stone—small, metallic, true. He didn't elaborate. His jaw tightened, and I could see him weighing what else to say, what else to keep locked away.\n\nThe balcony door creaked behind us, and we both pivoted toward the sound, but no one emerged. Just the old wood settling, or maybe the wind.\n\nI tasted metal and gripped the balustrade because the sea's salt grew too loud. \"That wasn't your burden to carry.\"\n\nHe smiled without humor. \"Wasn't yours either.\" He set the glove down on the stone, his fingers lingering on the wool like he was reluctant to let it go. \"But we both know how that goes.\"\n\nBecause he named duty, I couldn't name the night. I wanted to ask whether the debt included me, or whether he kept that part in a separate ledger; instead I reached for another small truth.\n\n\"Still curse in Italian when you're frustrated?\"\n\nHe huffed a breath that could have been a laugh. \"Cazzo, sì.\"\n\nThe R rolled like gravel, exactly like permission to cross a line. The sound hit something deep in my chest, muscle memory from nights when his voice had been softer, closer.\n\n\"Some things don't change.\" Then quieter, almost to himself: \"Bella testarda.\"\n\nThe endearment slipped out like he hadn't meant to say it, and his eyes widened slightly, as if he'd surprised himself. We both pretended not to notice the way my breath caught.\n\nWe skated around the big thing—no names, no retellings, only the scratch of wool between us and the tiny, stubborn moth under the fairy light. I counted on my thumb like marking exhibits. The moth's wings were translucent in the bulb's glow, delicate as tissue paper.\n\n\"Two conditions.\" I held up a finger. \"This week belongs to Sofia and Dante.\"\n\nHe nodded, waiting.\n\nI raised a second finger. \"We don't relitigate old cases.\"\n\n\"Agreed.\" He picked up the glove, smoothed the wool with his thumb. \"Clean slate.\"\n\nI folded my hand over the wool glove like closing a file. The fabric was soft against my palm, still holding the warmth of his skin. \"Buona notte, Marco.\"\n\n\"Buonanotte, Lena.\"\n\nI reached for the door handle, but his voice stopped me. \"Lena.\" My name in his mouth like a question he'd been practicing. I turned back, and he was looking at me with something that made my chest tight. The fairy lights cast shadows across his face, making him look younger somehow, like the boy I'd known before we'd learned to armor ourselves in law and obligation. \"I never stopped—\" His voice cracked, and he swallowed hard. \"I need you to know that whatever happened between us, whatever I did wrong—\"\n\n\"Marco.\" I stepped toward him without meaning to, my hand lifting like it had a will of its own.\n\nHe caught my fingers, his thumb brushing across my knuckles. \"Tell me you feel nothing. Tell me this is just old habit, and I'll walk away.\" His eyes searched mine, desperate. \"But if there's even a chance—\"\n\nWhy do we always find our courage on balconies in the dark?",
