urteen nights of falling asleep to the sound of waves and waking up to the smell of lemon blossoms and the knowledge that this was temporary, that I would leave, that leaving was the point.\n\nI counted the practicalities—the ferry schedule, my clients back in New York who would scream if I rearranged, the cost of a last-minute flight. Then I counted my loyalty to Sofia, which had accrued interest through years of messy breakfasts when one of us had hit rock bottom.\n\nThe numbers didn't add up to a clear answer, so I stopped counting.\n\nI pushed the Marco card closer to him on the mock-table, feeling the pin prick my fingertip. \"Objection sustained.\" A tiny bright dot of blood bloomed on the paper and I touched it with my thumb until the sting steadied me.\n\nMarco glanced down, saw the smear, smiled in that small, private way he does when he registers compromise. The expression transformed his whole face, softening the lines around his eyes that hadn't been there when we were twenty-five and stupid enough to think love was simple.\n\nSofia clapped once, too loud in the lemon-sweet air. \"Perfetto.\"\n\nI folded the paper card into the slot I'd just made, the blood smear disappearing into the crease like evidence I'd never been here at all.",
