      "content": "Lena Castillo found herself in the Monastery lemon grove terrace, twilight. Enzo set the tray down with a soft clink; the chipped ceramic cup nudged mine and left a ring of damp on the terracotta. He tapped the clipboard so the paper rattled. \"You or him?\"\n\nI lifted the cup but didn't drink, just held it while my pulse hammered against my wrists. The chip was sharp under my thumb—I kept tracing it. Because he was waiting, I read the top line: revised vendor schedule, late-night deliveries, an extra rehearsal for the cousins' entrance, a morning window with the florist at eight. My shoulders went rigid. Enzo watched the paper as if it might sprout an argument.\n\n\"Need an answer.\"\n\nThe printer-ink smell on the board made my fingers itch. Marco leaned on the low wall that framed the grove, tape flakes stuck to the knuckle of one hand where he'd wrestled place cards; when I looked up, the light carved his jaw in hard, clean planes. He shrugged.\n\nHours later, after the family dinner had ended, I found myself back on the terrace. \"I can call after dinner.\"\n\nHis Italian sang in the vowels—short, practical. That answer reached me because Sofia had already built the day into an edifice and the florist's deadline was the keystone; if the keystone shifted, the whole thing would crumble. I wanted to say yes—for Sofia, for the wedding that mattered to her—but my throat closed around the word.\n\n\"Great. Now I'm the deciding—\"\n\n\"You handle timelines.\" Enzo's eyes flicked to Marco. \"Logistics. Two of you, same villa. Sì o no?\"\n\nThe decision stopped being theoretical; it demanded signatures, literal ones. I traced the line of the schedule with my thumb, imagining the two-week block filling up with vendor calls, tastings, and twenty-two dinners where we would be physically proximate in ways I'd avoided for years. The want was there—to help Sofia, to be useful—but it crashed against the fear of what proximity to Marco might cost me. He didn'