 the inside of a shell.\n\nI gesture at the scattered debris, the plastic bottle spinning lazily in the current. \"You brought me to a crime scene.\"\n\nThe words slip out before I can stop them, because banter rebuilds the scaffolding when tides unsettle everything.\n\nHe laughs, the sound rough and quick against the cliffs. My mouth tastes of salt. His laugh dies into something softer, more careful, and he glances at me sideways as if measuring my mood against the light.\n\nI adjusted my sleeve and pivoted the glass slowly.\n\nHe closes the last few feet without taking his hand off the rail; his arm grazes mine and the contact is small and deliberate, as meticulous as his silence has been. The fabric of his shirt catches briefly on my sleeve, a tiny friction that speaks louder than words.\n\nHe runs his free fingers along his collar, leaving it disheveled. \"Questa cala—\" The Italian sneaks in like a private key. He pauses, switching back to English. \"It's the only place I come when I need to think.\"\n\nHe turns to look at me then, and the light catches a freckle near his jaw. His hand slides from the rail and finds my elbow. The touch is not possessive; it is exact. He leans in. I can map the calluses on his thumb, rough from years of monastery work, from handling stone and wood and the practical weight of other people's ceremonies.\n\nHe kisses me. It is slow at first—lips tasting of salt and sunscreen and the grapefruit soap they use in the monastery bathrooms—and the stone under my thighs presses through fabric I hadn't realized would thin at the seam. My hand goes to his chest the way one puts a palm on a table for balance, except his linen is warm and there is grit in the weave that transfers to my skin. His heartbeat drums against my palm, quick and unsteady.\n\nHis breath is warm against my neck. \"Bella.\"\n\nThe word vibrates through bone, settles somewhere behind my ribs where I thought I'd built better walls.\n\nI press my palms against his chest, creating distance. \"Stop.\"\n\nThe word comes out uneven, and I know that if I don't pull away now, I'll lose the last shred of control that keeps me from falling completely into something that could destroy everything I've worked to rebuild. My foot catches a loose pebble and I stumble once, catching myself on the rail, fingers skittering over stone that feels too smooth, too willing to let me slip.\n\nHe reaches for my face—gentle, hesitant. \"Lena—\"\n\nI shake my head, pulling back further, the tenderness in his touch too much like David's had been in those final weeks when he'd tried to convince me we could still make it work. \"No.\"\n\nI pull back, pressing the pad of my thumb against the edge of a blue flip-flop wedged between two rocks, the €3,50 sticker half-lifted and gritty with salt, and the tacky plastic under my fingertip is absurdly, perfectly ordinary. The tide pool beside it reflects a slice of sky, fractured by my shadow. Why is it that the most beautiful moments always come with the most ridiculous debris?",
