re's something desperate beneath the logistics, something that makes my chest tighten with recognition. He needs this wedding to happen, needs it with an intensity that has nothing to do with love and everything to do with survival.\n\nI start to speak, then catch myself. \"Who's going to—\" The words die because saying 'I will' aloud feels dangerous in a monastery courtyard where promises bounce off stone, and if I sign those papers, I'll be bound to this charade until death do us part or his secrets destroy us both.\n\nThe practical details crowd my mind like armor against the emotional minefield spreading across the breakfast table. My shoes are sensible flats, broken in and reliable. My bag contains backup pens and emergency supplies. I am prepared for bureaucracy, if not for the way Marco's fingers drum against his thigh in a rhythm that matches my accelerating pulse.\n\nDante appears with a tray of pastries that smell like butter and orange blossom. He sets it down with theatrical flourish, his movements loose and easy in contrast to the something electric passes between us between the rest of us.\n\n\"Anyone need backup for the bureaucracy run?\" He grins, stealing a piece of Sofia's croissant.\n\nThe pastries glisten with sugar crystals that catch the light like scattered diamonds. Steam rises from their golden surfaces, carrying the scent of citrus and vanilla. My stomach clenches with hunger I've been ignoring since dawn, but reaching for food feels like admitting weakness.\n\nSofia laughs, bright and calculated. She slides the vendor list closer to me, fingertips lingering on the paper's edge.\n\n\"Lena's got this.\" Her voice carries absolute certainty. \"Don't you, honey?\"\n\nHer confidence in my competence feels both flattering and manipulative. She knows I'll handle the paperwork because I always handle the details others avoid. It's my role in this strange dance we're performing—the reliable one, the one who makes things work while others make grand gestures.\n\nMarco reaches across when wind lifts the paper; his fingers brush the scar on my palm where glass cut deep three years ago. The contact sends electricity up my arm, and I see recognition flicker in his eyes—he remembers the accident, remembers holding my bleeding hand while we waited for the ambulance. He pulls his hand back quickly, but the damage is done.\n\n\"Office has everything we need.\" His voice rougher now, like sandpaper.\n\nThe scar tingles where he touched it, a phantom pain that has nothing to do with old wounds and everything to do with the way he's looking at me now. Like he's seeing past the careful walls I've constructed, past the practical exterior to something more vulnerable underneath.\n\nI fold the list into my bag next to my backup pen. \"Right. I'll—\"\n\n\"Wait.\" Marco's interruption cuts sharp through the morning air. His elbow finds the sticky wine stain as he leans forward, drawing out each word like he's explaining contract terms. \"Ledger key's on the sacristan's table. Under the wooden rosary box.\"\n\nHis knowledge of the monastery's inner workings surprises me. He's been here less than a week, but he speaks with the familiarity of someone who's mapped every corner, catalogued every hiding place. I wonder what else he's discovered in his nocturnal wanderings.\n\nSofia claps once, sharp as a judge's gavel.\n\n\"Perfect.\" She waves my hand in dismissal. \"Grab us some real coffee on your way back?\"\n\nHer dismissal stings more than it should. I'm being sent on an errand while the real players remain at the table, and we all know it. But I need the escape, need the breathing room that distance will provide.\n\nThe cicadas resume their racket, their song rising and falling like waves against the cliffs. A gull shrieks over the water, its cry sharp and desperate. I stand and the chair protests with a rusty squeak that echoes off the stone walls. My cup leaves a coffee ring on the table that mirrors his—two perfect circles intersecting at the edges, overlapping in ways that feel too symbolic to ignore.\n\nTwenty minutes later, I find myself in the village bar ordering espresso. The practical details crowd my mind like armor against the emotional minefield spreading across the breakfast table. My shoes are sensible flats, broken in and reliable. My bag contains backup pens and emergency supplies. I am prepared for bureaucracy, if not for the way Marco's fingers drum against his thigh in a rhythm that matches my accelerating pulse.\n\nAfter collecting the coffee, I make my way back to the office. I head for the narrow stairs that lead down to the office and whatever paperwork waits there, my footsteps echoing in the morning stillness like a countdown to something I'm not ready to face.",
