 breeze. I straighten the vendor receipt with two fingers, aligning its edges with the coaster's rim. \"I'm working.\"\n\nSofia's face hardens. She leans forward, her voice losing its sweetness. The cushions on her chair compress under her weight, the fabric whispering against itself. \"Bullshit.\" A pause. \"This is about the other night, isn't it?\"\n\nShe reaches for my hand, her fingers soft but insistent. The wedding ring on her finger is different from Marco's—older, more ornate, with tiny diamonds that catch the light. \"Whatever you're afraid—\"\n\n\"I won't mess this up for you.\" If I let myself feel anything for him again, I'll lose the only family I have left.\n\nThe words hang between us, obscuring what we mean. Sofia's grip tightens, and I see something flicker across her face—recognition, maybe, or the first crack in whatever plan she's been building. I pull my hand free and move toward the door, my footsteps muffled by the thick Persian rug that covers most of the suite's floor.\n\n\"Lena.\" Her voice stops me at the threshold. I turn back, my hand still on the door handle, and she's watching me with an expression I can't read. \"What happened three years ago?\"\n\nMy throat closes. The question hangs in the space between us, heavy with everything I've never said. Through the window, I can hear the distant sound of Marco's voice calling instructions to someone in the courtyard below. I open my mouth, then close it again, the truth burning behind my teeth like a shard of glass I can't swallow.",
