ilo sul suo cuscino?\"\n\nThe command came out mangled, but he understood. He tucked the bill into his shirt pocket.\n\n\"Sì.\"\n\nHe paused, studying my face with those careful eyes. \"E per colazione?\"\n\n\"What if he's already awake?\" The question came out sharper than I intended.\n\n\"Then I wait.\"\n\nHis answer came too quickly, too rehearsed. Something in his tone made me narrow my eyes. Too practiced. Too smooth.\n\n\"You've done this before.\"\n\nHe peered at me with a small, conspiratorial smile but said nothing. The seconds stack up without words between us like a held breath.\n\n\"Io parlerò al ricevimento. Poi lo cerco.\" The words came quieter now, like a confession in chambers.\n\n\"Sei sicura?\"\n\nI hooked my fingers through the thin linen bag on my shoulder where Abuela's lace peeked out and thought of the file, the accusation, Dante's steady face, Gianna's careful silence, Marco's guilt.\n\n\"Sì.\" I paused, then added with a rueful smile, \"Fair enough.\"\n\nA door slammed somewhere in the corridor, followed by hurried footsteps on stone. The sound jarred me back to reality, reminding me that even in life my instincts flee to the courtroom.\n\nI handed him the folded square—note wrapped around the key, the Italian scrawl visible on the top. He smelled of orange zest peel and espresso, a scent that pulled my brain back to the morning when he fixed the coffee machine after we'd argued about seatings. He tucked the note into a pocket and folded the twenty into his hand like an accountant verifying payment, then cocked his head.\n\n\"Buona fortuna, avvocata.\"\n\n\"Gracias.\" It slipped out automatic, lighter than I wanted.\n\nHe stepped out into the wet corridor, but then stopped. Turned back. His hand found the doorframe, and for a moment he just looked at me—really glared, like he was memorizing something.\n\n\"What you wrote in that note.\" His voice dropped to barely above a whisper. \"You meant it?\"\n\nMy throat went dry. The words I'd scrawled in broken Italian felt exposed now, dangerous. \"I don't—\" I wanted to lie, to deflect, to cross-examine my way out of the truth. But something in his eyes made me strip away every defense I'd ever built, the same defenses that had kept me safe while I dissected other people's broken hearts for profit.\n\n\"Yes.\" The word came out raw, unguarded. \"Every word.\"\n\nHe stepped closer, inches away, and I could feel the warmth radiating from his skin. His fingers brushed against mine where they gripped the doorframe, and I forgot how to breathe. \"Then you should know,\" he said, \"you\\'re braver than you think.\"\n\nThe words hung between us, unfinished, heavy with possibility.",
