 away. Evidence has a chain of custody and so do reputations.\n\nThe woman beside me shifts in her seat, eyeing the paper. She leans closer, perfume heavy with jasmine.\n\n\"Beautiful ceremony.\"\n\nHer mouth pinches. \"Shame about the... distraction.\"\n\nI tilt my chin. Permission and warning in one movement.\n\nMarco stands at the end of the row, shoulders like a wall. When he catches my eye he doesn't smile—just nods once. Apology and alliance rolled into one gesture. He smells like sunblock and rosemary from whatever the kitchen staff rubbed on the bread.\n\nHis voice stays low, meant only for me. \"Everything looks perfect.\"\n\n\"I'd like to—\" The word slips out before I can stop it. \"Loaded question.\"\n\nHe steps closer, blocking the sun. \"Which witness would that be?\"\n\nThe priest raises his hands toward the couple. \"You may kiss the bride.\"\n\nThe applause comes thin and puzzled, like someone testing crystal for hairline cracks. I stay put with the program folded hard between my fingers. Moving means surrender. Sitting still means defense.\n\nA champagne flute shatters somewhere behind me, crystal exploding against stone.\n\nShoes scuff. Someone mutters behind me, voice sharp with gossip-hunger.\n\n\"How messy.\"\n\n\"Messier than most,\" another voice agrees.\n\nMarco leans close. Salt grit at the corner of his mouth, breath warm against my ear. \"Stay with her, okay?\"\n\nI press my clutch against my ribs instead of answering. The program crinkles inside. My thumb covers the words *legal records* so they're under skin instead of headline.\n\nThe priest finishes. Sofia and Dante turn toward us and the crowd reads like an open book with half the pages torn out—curiosity, judgment, pity in equal measure. Champagne carts roll forward like apologetic ships.\n\nSofia catches my eye across the sea of faces. Her smile wavers for just a second—a crack in the porcelain.\n\n\"Lena?\" Her voice carries over the crowd. \"Everything all right?\"\n\n\"The view 