      "content": "Lena Castillo found herself in the Private wine cellar under the monastery, late evening. The cellar door thuds shut behind us. My palms slip against the wood. Cool air wraps around my sundress; old oak and citron rind press into my nose, and someone has stuck an Esselunga receipt to a barrel with the corner flapping like a tiny desperate flag. Marco stands with his shoulder braced against a rack of bottles, dust motes drifting between the glass, and he looks too steady for the way my breath wants to trip.\n\nI pressed my temple against the cool stone wall.\n\nHe reaches into his jacket pocket and draws out the wedding program, edges soft from folding, my handwriting scrawled in the margin—tiny loops, an abbreviation for objection, a cross-out where I tried to be funny and failed. The paper smells like candle wax and the faint sweetness of limoncello that dried sticky on the step outside. His thumb hovers over my scrawl like he's afraid he'll smudge it. He holds it out.\n\n\"This yours?\" His voice catches on something rough.\n\nI twist a loose strand from my face. The curl won't stay. \"Kept it like evidence.\"\n\nHe shifts, his shoulder measuring the restraint he's been practicing. The bottles behind him catch the dim light filtering through the single window, amber and green glass throwing patterns on the stone walls.\n\n\"Evidence of what?\" He flips the program open, thumbs the corner where my tiny notes drifted into a doodle. \"You planning to cross-examine me, counselor?\"\n\nMy words come quick, clipped. \"Might have to.\" I press my lips together. The taste of wedding cake frosting still clings to my tongue, too sweet now. \"I didn't tell you because—\"\n\nThe paper whispers against his fingers as he closes the program.\n\n\"Because?\"\n\n\"Because silence felt safer than watching everything blow up.\" I shove my hands into my dress pockets. The fabric bunches awkwardly, and I can feel the outline of my phone, the sharp edge of a mint I forgot about. \"When I was sixteen, I kept my father's affair secret for months. Thought I was protecting my mother.\"\n\nHe goes still.\n\n\"Learned that silence can masquerade as kindness.\" Spanish edges into my throat. \"Dios mío, it turns into poison.\"\n\n\"So you decided for both of us.\" He folds the program closed, then opens it again. The paper rustles between his fingers like dried leaves. His jaw works, and I can see the muscle ticking beneath the skin.\n\n\"I decided—\" My voice cracks. The sound echoes off the stone walls, bouncing back at us from the shadows between the wine racks. \"I'm terrified of wanting something I might destroy just by wanting it.\"\n\nHe steps closer. His shoulder presses against mine; the rack of bottles stands witness, wine labels a line of silent jurors. The coolness of the cellar seems to concentrate around us, making the warmth of his body more noticeable. His hand finds mine—not dramatic, just fingers aligning with mine the way two pieces that have been trimmed and stacked eventually fit.\n\n\"Lena.\" He waits until I meet his eyes. No charm, no deflection. The gold flecks in the brown remind me of sunlight through amber bottles, and I realize I've been cataloguing the details of his face without meaning to—the slight scar above his left eyebrow, the way his mouth curves even when he's not smiling. \"I'm not going anywhere.\"\n\n\"You don't know that.\" The words flinch out of me. My free hand finds the rough stone wall behind me, needing something solid to press against. \"People always think they won't leave until—\"\n\n\"Until what?\" He cuts me off, his voice sharper now.\n\nI don't— The words stick in my throat. \"Until they do.\"\n\nHe watches my mouth while I say it, then closes the distance between us with the slow economy of someone who has practiced restraint for years and decides restraint is the lie. His hand slides up from mine to the curve of my wrist and he presses, not hard, just enough to anchor. I can feel my pulse jumping against his thumb like a trapped bird.\n\n\"Then we'll figure it out.\" His voice drops lower. \"As we go.\"\n\nHe leans in, within arm's reach, and I can count the flecks of gold in his brown eyes, close enough that his breath mingles with mine and carries the faint taste of the prosecco from upstairs. The wedding program crinkles between us, and his free hand comes up to trace the line of my jaw, thumb brushing across my cheek with the kind of reverence that makes my knees forget how to hold me upright.\n\n\"Marco.\" His name breaks on my lips like a confession, like a prayer I didn't know I'd been holding.\n\nHis forehead touches mine, and I can feel the question he's asking without words, the way his thumb stills against my pulse point, waiting. The silence between us hums with everything we haven't said, everything we've been dancing around for months. My heart hammers so hard I'm sure he can feel it through my skin.\n\n\"Tell me what you want,\" he whispers, and the words ghost across my lips. \"No more silence. No more deciding for both of us.\" Because whatever I say next will either open the door to everything I've been afraid to hope for or close it forever.",
