.\"\n\nI catch the loose hair from my temple—habit, diagnostic—buying myself another second to think. \"Literal lock or emotional metaphor?\"\n\nMarco's smile tightens in that particular way it does when he's deciding whether to be tender or blunt. He chooses both. \"Sì.\"\n\nThe word sits between us, not quite a promise but not empty either. He searches for something else, then lets it go. His shoulders lift slightly. \"Lock whatever you want. A drawer. Some stupid box.\" He touches the stone railing with two fingers. \"Or don't lock anything. Just—\"\n\n\"Keep it close!\" Enzo's voice carries up like a stone skipping water, mischief tucked at the edges but something like benediction underneath.\n\nMarco turns his head just enough for me to see the light catch his profile, the way the moon picks out a freckle near his temple. \"I want you to have something that belonged to me.\" He pauses. \"Not words. Not plans.\"\n\nI close my fist around the key. The metal is warm—not the heat of exertion but the comfortable, human heat of something kept close to skin; the orange zest leaf catches the moon and looks almost like a real leaf, fragile and ridiculous. My training runs a checklist—risk, relevance, cost—and then the checklist folds up like a paper I decided not to file. I slide the key into the interior pocket of my linen jacket because dresses without pockets are an aesthetic crime but also because pockets are practical.\n\nMarco watches me tuck it away. His voice goes quieter. \"Promise me you'll tell me when you're scared.\"\n\nNot a courtroom demand—quieter than that, like he's offering an unpaid favor. I hear the fatigue behind it, the part of his chest that learned to hold other people's needs before his own.\n\nI shrug one shoulder. \"I'll tell you when I litigate you into silence.\"\n\nIt lands as a joke that isn't entirely a joke. He smiles—real, not teasing this time—and Enzo claps once, soft, like applause from a bench. The party downstairs thins; a glass b