      "content": "Lena Castillo found herself in the Small ante-room off the chapel, windows open to the bergamot grove; a drying rack with citrine linens nearby, a single flickering candle from the reception left behind. I push the narrow ante-room door open. The table waits like evidence, and he's there with sleeves rolled to the elbow, forearms dusted with flour where he's been kneading something. The air tastes of rosemary and old wood. On the table, the stamped court cover sits square and official, and a photograph—folded small enough to hide in a palm—peeks from the crease. A blue supermarket price sticker, 1,95€, curls from the table leg.\n\nThe smell of yeast rises from whatever he's been working—bread, maybe, or focaccia. His hands still carry the ghost of flour, white dust settled into the creases of his knuckles. He's positioned himself angled so he can see both the door and the papers, like he's been waiting but won't admit it.\n\n\"The original.\" His fingers hover over the court cover like it might bite back.\n\nI straighten an already-straight napkin. \"Figured you wouldn't want to see it.\"\n\nThe seconds stack up without words between us, filled with the distant sound of someone sweeping in the courtyard below. My throat feels dry, the way it does before difficult testimony. I watch his shoulders rise and fall with controlled breathing.\n\nI pressed my temple and turned the glass slowly.\n\nHe lifts the photograph from the table with careful fingers and the room shrinks around the small square: a boy about twelve, missing teeth, mud on one knee—Luca. Marco's mouth goes tight. The same way his father's did when choosing silence over screaming.\n\nThe photograph trembles slightly in his grip. I can see the worn edges where someone—Sofia, probably—has handled it countless times. The boy's smile is gap-toothed and genuine, caught mid-laugh at something beyond the camera's frame.\n\nA door slams somewhere in the house, followed by quick footsteps on the stairs.\n\n\"Couldn't leave it to whispers.\" He sets the photo down, pushes it toward the center of the table. \"People fill gaps with—\"\n\n\"Stories.\" His thumb traces the stamp on the cover. I taste copper, like biting my tongue during depositions. My brain reaches for legalese—public records, chain of custody, procedural clarification—but I swallow it.\n\nThe candle flame wavers, casting shifting shadows across the legal documents. I catalog details the way I do in depositions: the precise fold of the photograph, the way Marco's signet ring catches the light when he moves his hand, the faint stain on the table's edge that looks like wine.\n\n\"Should've told you sooner.\"\n\nHe exhales through his nose. \"Don't need your legal armor right now, Lena.\" His voice catches on my name. \"Just need to know what happens next. For Sofia.\"\n\nHis fingers drum against the photograph. I outline what comes next. Registry copy, short statement of representation and dates, no extra narrative, delivery through Enzo to Sofia's hand, posted to the family registry with receipt.\n\nI tugged my collar and grabbed the edge of the table.\n\nHe listens without interrupting, which surprises me. Usually he cuts through my explanations with questions or challenges, but tonight he just nods at the right moments, his eyes never leaving the photograph.\n\n\"Check-ins.\" He runs his hand down his face. \"Twenty minutes. You tell me when you're traveling—\"\n\n\"I tell you when I need space.\"\n\nI roll the proposal around in my mouth. \"Two visits a month. One weekend here, one in New York.\" I cross my arms, uncross them. \"Forty-eight hours notice if plans change.\"\n\nThe words sound clinical even to me, like we're negotiating a custody agreement instead of whatever this is. But maybe that's what we need—clear boundaries, defined expectations. The lawyer in me approves even as something deeper rebels against reducing this to terms and conditions.\n\n\"No instant responses.\" He gestures at the gap that separated us. \"We respect time zones and court schedules and—\"\n\n\"Whatever else gets in the way.\"\n\nHe slides the photograph back toward me. \"Used to steal bergamot from Nonna's tree. Hide them in his pockets.\" A ghost of a smile. \"Dante says that's how he learned to cook—watching Luca raid the kitchen.\"\n\nI let the corners of the photo brush my thumbnail. The scar on my left palm pricks—old glass, old guilt. \"Lo siento.\" The Spanish slips out before I can catch it. \"I should have—I let the rumors...\"\n\nThe boy in the photograph stares up at us with eyes that look like Marco's, that same intensity even at twelve. I wonder if he had Marco's stubborn streak too, if he argued about bedtime and homework the way Sofia probably does.\n\nHe closes his fingers over mine on the photo. Just for a second. \"No vows.\" His eyes find mine. \"Small promises. Truth, even when it's ugly.\"\n\n\"That's not—\" I stop. \"Bene.\" The word comes out mangled, my accent butchering the vowels.\n\nWe lean in until the dying candle threads light across our faces. Our mouths meet—brief, precise, like sealing an envelope. When we break apart, I reach for my jacket and head toward the door.",
