      "content": "\"Caffè?\" Marco called from the kitchen, his voice rough around the edges like he'd been awake longer than he'd admit. I pushed through the doorway and found him juggling a tray—white cups rattling against saucers, a plate of those paper-thin cookies balanced in his other hand like he was defying physics. The morning light felt different somehow, softer than the harsh fluorescents of last night's crisis, but my shoulders still carried the weight of everything unsaid between us. Abuela's empanada dough sat under a tea towel, the mason jar smudged with floury fingerprints. Someone had been checking on it.\n\nThe linens on the drying rack were still warm from the sun, smelling like that detergent with too much lavender that made me sneeze if I buried my face in the towels.\n\nHe grinned, one eyebrow cocked, steadying the tray with fingers that bore a white scar under the thumb—old pruning accident, he'd told me once. I moved toward the counter because the smell of fried dough was making my stomach growl, and my phone started vibrating against the stone like an angry wasp.\n\nOFFER in all caps. Manhattan firm. The one I'd been waiting on for three months. If I didn't respond by noon tomorrow, they'd move to their backup candidate. Partner track. The kind of position that doesn't knock twice.\n\nI flipped the screen and read while pouring coffee, skimmed to the salary line because old habits die hard. The number made me grip the cup until the porcelain creaked.\n\nMarco watched my face change. He set the tray down slowly.\n\n\"What happened?\"\n\n\"Job offer.\" I set the cup down harder than necessary. \"Manhattan firm.\"\n\nThe words hung there while I tried to calculate time zones and billable hours and how long a person could realistically live in two countries before something snapped.\n\nHe placed a biscotto next to my cup, his fingers lingering on the plate.\n\n\"So you take it.\" He shrugged, but his jaw tightened. \"Fly when you need to. Come back when you can.\"\n\nNo drama. Just logistics. We traded details like we were negotiating a contract, which maybe we were.\n\nI squinted at the fine print.\n\n\"Remote twenty percent, travel two months per quarter.\" I stared up. \"Emergency response within seventy-two hours.\"\n\nHe laughed, but it came out hollow. His hand found the back of his neck.\n\n\"Seventy-two hours? Madonna, they really think they own you.\"\n\nI pressed my palm against the mason jar, letting the cool glass steady me.\n\n\"What if I get there and remember why I ran away in the first place?\"\n\nSomething shifted in his expression. He leaned back against the counter, crossing his arms.\n\n\"Then you decide again.\"\n\nThe deadline wasn't theoretical anymore. My chest constricted.\n\n\"Wait—\"\n\nHe raised his hands in mock surrender.\n\n\"Overruled by reality.\" His smile faded. \"But first—\"\n\nHe pulled out a small iron key, the old-fashioned kind that belonged on a ring with maybe three others. Heavy, worn smooth at the edges. He had one clipped to his keychain; this was the spare to Enzo's place, the one that opened the little lock by the pantry.\n\nHe held it out between us.\n\nThe metal was cool, then warm under my fingers.\n\n\"Don't make this symbolic.\"\n\n\"Too late.\" His mouth quirked up at one corner.\n\nI closed my fist around the key.\n\n\"Ground rules. Check-ins when we travel. No disappearing acts.\"\n\n\"Deal.\"\n\nWe mapped it out across the table—blocked months, dawn conference calls, return trips timed around olive harvest and the neighbor kid's soccer schedule since his ball kept landing on our terrace. He corrected my pronunciation of rosmarino, patient as a language teacher.\n\n\"Ros-ma-REE-no.\"\n\nI tried it three times before getting close, called it rozmarino once and made him laugh.\n\nWhen we finished, the calendar looked less like a compromise and more like something that might actually work.\n\nI tested the water one more time.\n\n\"If things go sideways, we tell the truth first. No protecting each other's feelings.\"\n\nHe looked at me then, the teasing dropping away. Something solid settled in his expression.\n\n\"Promise me, Lena.\"\n\nThe key bit into my palm where I'd been gripping it too tight. Marco's eyes held mine, waiting for an answer that felt like it would change everything. I opened my mouth to give him the easy promise, the safe one that would keep us both protected.\n\nInstead, what came out was, \"I think I'm already in too deep to make promises like that.\"\n\nHis breath caught. The space between us felt electric, charged with everything we hadn't said.\n\n\"What do you mean?\"\n\nMy phone buzzed again on the counter—probably the firm following up, probably urgent. I didn't look. I couldn't look away from Marco's face, from the way he was watching me like I held something fragile and precious in my hands.\n\n\"I mean I've spent my whole life running from anything that felt like this.\" The words scraped against my throat. \"And now I'm standing here holding your key, making plans like we're—\" I stopped, my heart hammering against my ribs. \"Like we're something real.\"",
